[{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8100","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1828-11-28","city"  :"Shad Parish","state"  :"NH","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8100.txt","description"  :"I have been in a quandary ever since I left thee, whether I had better accept the offer of Friend Collier, or nail myself down to my seat, for, verily, I could not be kept there otherwise","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"A","r_lastName"  :"Thayer","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8101","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1834-10-25","city"  :"Newburyport","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8101.txt","description"  :"I am disappointed in not seeing thee at this place and this time, as I called to apprise thee of the fact that at our meeting of the Essex County Anti-Slavery Society yesterday","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8102","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1834-11-03","city"  :"Haverhill","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8102.txt","description"  :"Several individuals, personally and politically thy friends, have suggested to me the idea of addressing thee in regard to thy sentiments in relation to slavery in the District of Columbia.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8103","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1836-02-20","city"  :"Haverhill","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8103.txt","description"  :"I send thee three small petitions, and will trouble thee no more for the present session.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8104","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1836-03-01","city"  :"Haverhill","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8104.txt","description"  :"I am greatly obliged to thee for thy account of the state of politics at Washington.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8106","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-01-16","city"  :"Philadelphia","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8106.txt","description"  :"How are the abolition petitions received?","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8107","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-03-13","city"  :"Boston","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8107.txt","description"  :"I send with this a copy of the report and resolutions of the committee on the subject of slavery and the right of petition.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8108","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-04-14","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8108.txt","description"  :"Our county anti-slavery society holds its quarterly meeting in this place on the 21st.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8109","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1836-08-27","city"  :"Haverhill","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8109.txt","description"  :"I have received a long letter in relation to Governor Everett from one of his personal friends...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Jeremiah","r_lastName"  :"Spofford","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8110","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1836-11-23","city"  :"Haverhill","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8110.txt","description"  :" I have just learned that a good deal of dissatisfaction exists in this village in regard to my connection with the 'Gazette.'","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Jeremiah","r_lastName"  :"Spofford","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8111","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1836-12-01","city"  :"Haverhill","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8111.txt","description"  :"I have felt rather unpleasantly about leaving the paper, and could I consistently with what I conceive to be my duty take such a course as would be satisfactory to its patrons, I would do so","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Jeremiah","r_lastName"  :"Spofford","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8112","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-00-13","city"  :"Boston","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8112.txt","description"  :"I am fearful that I am troubling thee too often with the question of slavery, but the deep interest I feel must be my excuse.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Robert","r_lastName"  :"Rantoul","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8113","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-06-14","city"  :"Newport","state"  :"RI","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8113.txt","description"  :"Thee hardly expected to hear from me at this place - certainly I did not expect to be here when I left Amesbury.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Elizabeth","r_lastName"  :"Whittier","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8114","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-07-04","city"  :"New York","state"  :"NY","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8114.txt","description"  :"I am lounging away my time here, not closely applying myself to anything, overseeing the sending out of petitions.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Elizabeth","r_lastName"  :"Whittier","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8115","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-08-06","city"  :"New York","state"  :"NY","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8115.txt","description"  :"I see all the French and Spanish ladies in the city. As a general thing they are not so beautiful as the American ladies.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Harriet","r_lastName"  :"Minot","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8116","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-08-21","city"  :"New York","state"  :"NY","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8116.txt","description"  :"The truth is, the 'small craft' of poetry in which we have indulged ourselves is not fitted for the voyage of Immortality. We shall perish, and verily our works will follow us.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Lucy","r_lastName"  :"Hooper","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8117","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1837-08-27","city"  :"Boston","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8117.txt","description"  :"I did not receive thy note until after my return from Brooklyn the other day, or I should have alluded to it when I saw thee.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Lucy","r_lastName"  :"Hooper","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8118","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1839-00-00","city"  :"Philadelphia","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8118.txt","description"  :"For myself, abolition has been to me its own 'exceeding great reward.'","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Elizabeth","r_lastName"  :"Neall","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8119","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1838-06-03","city"  :"Philadelphia","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8119.txt","description"  :"In regard to some political queries in thy letter of last spring, touching the course of the abolitionists in the presidential contest, I will answer briefly.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8120","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1838-08-16","city"  :"Philadelphia","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8120.txt","description"  :"Our cause here is slowly, and against unnumbered obstacles, going ahead.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"J","r_lastName"  :"Fuller","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8121","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1839-04-04","city"  :"Philadelphia","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8121.txt","description"  :"My fugitive poems have never been published, except a few in a late volume bound up with my abolition and incendiary verses.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Caleb","r_lastName"  :"Cushing","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8122","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1840-05-00","city"  :"Bucks County","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8122.txt","description"  :"My general health is about as usual - I fear not better. I have much pain in chest and head.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Elizabeth","r_lastName"  :"Whittier","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8123","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1840-06-12","city"  :"Newport","state"  :"RI","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8123.txt","description"  :"On reaching New York we received an accession to our company, Joseph John Gurney, Richard Mott, Samuel Parsons, and a large number of younger friends","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8124","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1840-07-02","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8124.txt","description"  :"I wish to contradict in terms as explicit as possible the rumor which thou mentions from Newport Yearly Meeting. It is most preposterously absurd. My abolitionism grows daily stronger","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Moses","r_lastName"  :"Cartland","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8125","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1840-07-13","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8125.txt","description"  :"Did I mention to thee in my letter from Newport a circumstance in relation to Richard Mott?","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8126","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1840-11-00","city"  :"Lynn","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8126.txt","description"  :"I was in Boston this week, and looked in twice upon the queer gathering of heterogeneous spirits at the Chardon Street chapel...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8127","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1841-03-00","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8127.txt","description"  :"Thy letter was heartily welcome, for I had been for some days too stupid and dull to feel any interest in things present, and naturally enough my mind wandered back to the past...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Harriet","r_lastName"  :"Minot","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8128","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1841-05-13","city"  :"Philadelphia","state"  :"PA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8128.txt","description"  :"I have been in company with Joseph Sturge, of England, at New York, Philadelphia, Wilmington, and Baltimore, endeavoring to do something for the cause of abolition...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Harriet","r_lastName"  :"Minot","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8129","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1842-07-00","city"  :"Lee","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8129.txt","description"  :"I like thy remarks about the Liberty party and its dangers, and I thank thee for thy friendly caution. I am not much affected by the whirl of politics.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8130","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1842-05-05","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8130.txt","description"  :"H. C. Wright, as I learn from the 'Liberator,' is going to England to discuss.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Harriet","r_lastName"  :"Minot","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8131","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1842-08-19","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8131.txt","description"  :"The serene, calm faith which breathes through thy letters rebukes at times my own restless and inquiring spirit.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8132","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1843-08-00","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8132.txt","description"  :"I should be heartily glad to visit Philadelphia, to sit with cousin Ann, and discuss upon the great problems of human life and destiny, and not upon those high abstractions alone, but upon the household things","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8133","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1845-01-24","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8133.txt","description"  :"Permit me, although a stranger to thee personally, to express my gratitude for and heartfelt admiration of thy letter to thy constituents on the annexation of Texas.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Hale","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8134","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1845-11-00","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8134.txt","description"  :"There is nothing to alarm us in the overwhelming numbers of the two old parties. These parties are indeed evil and only evil, in consequence of their alliance with Slavery...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Gerrit","r_lastName"  :"Smith","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8135","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1846-09-16","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8135.txt","description"  :"I see by the papers that thy lecture in Faneuil Hall takes place on the 18th. There is one point which I wish to call thy attention to.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Hale","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8136","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1846-12-18","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8136.txt","description"  :"We are about starting our 'National Era' at Washington, and should be glad of a note of encouragement from thee.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Hale","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8137","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1847-02-21","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8137.txt","description"  :"What a sad state of things in Ireland! We have been trying to do something in this region. Our little meeting here has raised about fifty dollars.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ann","r_lastName"  :"Wendell","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8138","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1847-07-30","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8138.txt","description"  :"Pardon me for a suggestion or two. It is important that it should be understood that thou art disconnected entirely from the two old parties...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Hale","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8139","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1847-10-02","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8139.txt","description"  :"Ere this I suppose the result of the convention at Buffalo has reached thee. If not already, thou wilt soon be officially informed of it, when it will be expected of thee that thy position will be defined.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Hale","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8140","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1847-08-11","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8140.txt","description"  :"I wrote thee a hasty line the other day with reference to the Buffalo nomination. I sincerely hope thou wilt not feel thyself called upon to decline that nomination.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"John","r_lastName"  :"Hale","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8141","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1848-07-27","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8141.txt","description"  :"I would like to go to the Buffalo convention, but my health forbids the idea. What will be done there? I would go for Van Buren - if Hale decline - if he would come out in favor of abolition in the District of Columbia.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Moses","r_lastName"  :"Cartland","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8142","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1849-05-10","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8142.txt","description"  :"We have had a dreary spring a gray haze in the sky a dim, beam-shorn sun a wind from the northeast, cold as if sifted through all the ices of frozen Labrador...","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Grace","r_lastName"  :"Greenwood","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8143","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1853-10-21","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8143.txt","description"  :"What marvelous weather ! Amidst the autumnal opulence of the last two weeks, I have lived more than royally.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Ralph Waldo","r_lastName"  :"Emerson","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8144","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1855-00-00","city"  :"Amesbury","state"  :"MA","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8144.txt","description"  :"Elizabeth has been reading Browning's poem (' Men and Women'), and she tells me it is great.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Lucy","r_lastName"  :"Larcom","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"},{"id"  :"ltr_jgw8145","type"  :"letter","date"  :"1848-02-23","city"  :"Washington","state"  :"MD","country"  :"US","fileName"  :"ltr_jgw8145.txt","description"  :"Ere this thou hast doubtless heard of the sudden illness of the venerable Adams. At a late hour last night he was still living, but sinking fast.","source"  :"78","firstName"  :"John","lastName"  :"Whittier","pedigree"  :"","r_firstName"  :"Charles","r_lastName"  :"Sumner","r_pedigree"  :"","r_type"  :"individual"}]